<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12093o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12093o">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12093o"> 93(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> &mdash; jests, plate of bones, / trip up,</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><i>Farces pendant le repas</i>.&mdash; A la fin du d&icirc;ner, on fait passer un plat dans lequel on a plac&eacute; des os. Il est recouvert d&apos;une serviette. Ceux qui ne sont pas au courant des farces du pays soul&egrave;vent la serviette, et aper&ccedil;oivent les os, aux grands &eacute;clats de rire de tous ceux qui assistent au repas. <br><i>An Drezen</i>. &mdash; Souvent, apr&egrave;s le d&icirc;ner ou m&ecirc;me avant, quand les gens de la noce se prom&egrave;nent par les chemins, ils sont souvent arr&ecirc;t&eacute;s par des ficelles auxquelles sont attach&eacute;es des &eacute;pines et que des gamins ont tendu au travers de la route. <br><font color="green">[<i>Jokes during the meal</i>. At the end of dinner, a plate on which there are bones is passed round. It is covered with a napkin. Those who don&apos;t know the local jokes will lift the napkin and then see the bones, to great peals of laughter from everybody else. <br><i>An Drezen</i>. &mdash; Often, after and sometimes even before dinner, when the wedding guests walk along the roads, they are often stopped by string on which thorns have been attached and which kids have tied across the road.]</font> <small> Paul-Yves S&eacute;billot, <a name="RDTP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#RDTP"><cite title="source">Traditions et coutumes de Basse Bretagne</cite></a> (1904) 354</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
